ce:section.ce:para:
The enzyme-like activity of the composite was also investigated by the chromogenic reaction of TMB [19]. In the presence of the nanozyme, the chromogenic TMB substrate is oxidized giving rise to oxTMB and, as a result, the colorless solution of TMB rapidly turns blue. Upon addition of the phenolic compound, the oxTMB is reduced back to TMB and the blue color of the solution fades. The kinetic parameters, i.e., the Michaelis-Menten constant (Km
                        ) and the maximum reaction velocity (vmax
                        ) of the MnO2/GQD as oxidase-mimicking were calculated using the Lineweaver-Burk plot [36,37]
                           , yielding
                         values of 0.11 mM and 24.4 × 10−8 M s−1, respectively [20]. Such values indicate that the nanozyme presents good catalytic performance, with a high affinity to the TMB substrate and a fast reaction rate [19]. For instance, in our previous work, the good kinetic parameters obtained for the MnO2/GQD composite enabled the colorimetric detection of antioxidants in food samples with high sensitivity [20]. Therefore, inspired by the capacity of the composite in detecting aromatic compounds through the chromogenic reaction of TMB, here the oxidase-like activity of the MnO2/GQD nanozyme was also explored as an indirect sensing platform to detect DA and CC by the color changes of the TMB solution.
